body_raw:
By definition, $S$ is linearly independent if for all $n>0,c_i\in F,s_i\in S$, we have that $c_1s_1 + \ldots + c_n s_n 
eq 0$ whenever $\{c_i\}
eq \{0\}$. Why do we restrict our attention to finite linear combinations? We could imagine a different definition: Set $S$ is "infinitely linearly independent" if for any indexing set $I$ and $c_i\in F,s_i\in S$, we have that $\sum_{i \in I} c_is_i 
eq 0$ whenever $\{c_i\}
eq \{0\}$. Why isn't this definition, which allows arbitrary subsets of $S$, useful?

